.TH WITHDRAWAL_PROJECTION 1 "2026-06-21" "finance/planning/annuity" "Annuity Planning Tools"
.SH NAME
withdrawal_projection \- project annuity-equivalent withdrawals from an equity-invested account
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B python withdrawal_projection.py
.I amount age gender state
.RB [ --joint-age
.IR AGE ]
.RB [ --joint-gender
.IR M|F ]
.RB [ --years
.IR N ]
.RB [ --model
.IR bootstrap|block|lognormal ]
.RB [ --block-length
.IR YEARS ]
.RB [ --seed
.IR INT ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B withdrawal_projection.py
simulates a single random 30-year path of a retirement strategy that does
.I not
buy an annuity but instead keeps the money invested in equities and each year
withdraws what a life annuity
.I would
pay on the current balance.
.PP
Starting from
.IR amount ,
for each projected year the program:
.IP 1. 4
Looks up the monthly life-annuity payout for the current balance at the current
age via
.BR annuity_quote (1)
(immediateannuities.com). Because the payout is linear in the premium, a single
$100,000 reference quote is fetched per age and scaled to the balance.
.IP 2. 4
Withdraws twelve times that monthly payout from the balance.
.IP 3. 4
Grows the remaining balance by that year's nominal equity return.
.IP 4. 4
Increments the age (and any joint age) by one and repeats.
.PP
Equity returns and CPI inflation are drawn
.I jointly
from the model selected by
.B --model
so the historical equity/inflation correlation is preserved. Results are
reported both in nominal dollars and in today's (inflation-deflated) dollars.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I amount
Starting amount invested (premium). Accepts plain digits, commas, or a leading
"$" (e.g. \fB1000000\fR, \fB1,000,000\fR, \fB$1,000,000\fR). Must be positive.
.TP
.I age
Age today. Integer 40\(en90 (the quote site's supported range).
.TP
.I gender
\fBM\fR or \fBF\fR (\fBmale\fR/\fBfemale\fR also accepted).
.TP
.I state
Two-letter US state code, e.g. \fBFL\fR, or \fBOTHER\fR.
.TP
.BI --joint-age " AGE"
Age of a joint (second) beneficiary, 40\(en90. Switches the quote to a joint-life
annuity. Must be given together with \fB--joint-gender\fR.
.TP
.BI --joint-gender " M|F"
Gender of the joint beneficiary. Must be given together with \fB--joint-age\fR.
.TP
.BI --years " N"
Number of years to project. Default \fB30\fR.
.TP
.BI --model " bootstrap|block|lognormal"
Equity/inflation return model (see \fBMODELS\fR). Default \fBbootstrap\fR.
.TP
.BI --block-length " YEARS"
Block size in years, used only with \fB--model block\fR. Default \fB5\fR.
.TP
.BI --seed " INT"
Seed for the random number generator, for reproducible paths. Default: random.
.SH MODELS
The return models are defined in
.BR equity_model.py ,
calibrated to paired S&P 500 nominal total returns and CPI annual-average
inflation for 1928\(en2025 (see
.BR market_data.py ).
.TP
.B bootstrap
IID historical bootstrap: each year is an actual historical year-pair drawn with
replacement. Preserves the empirical distribution (fat left tail, skew, and the
contemporaneous equity/inflation correlation). Recommended default for tail-risk
work; serial correlation between years is not preserved.
.TP
.B block
Circular moving-block bootstrap: resamples consecutive runs of
.B --block-length
years and stitches them together (wrapping past the end of the series).
Preserves serial correlation \(em notably the strong year-to-year persistence of
inflation \(em which widens the left tail of multi-year outcomes. Longer blocks
preserve more persistence.
.TP
.B lognormal
Draws from a bivariate normal fitted to (log(1+equity), log(1+inflation)).
Smooth and able to extrapolate beyond observed values, but has zero
skew/kurtosis and so understates tail risk. The fitted covariance still
reproduces the historical correlation.
.SH OUTPUT
A calibration header (model, sample span, equity arithmetic/geometric mean and
standard deviation, CPI mean and standard deviation, equity/inflation
correlation), followed by a year-by-year table: year, age, starting balance,
monthly payout (nominal and in today's dollars), that year's equity return and
inflation, and ending balance. Three summary lines report the ending balance in
nominal dollars, the ending balance in today's dollars, and the cumulative
inflation factor over the projection.
.SH ASSUMPTIONS AND CAVEATS
.IP \(bu 2
This models withdrawing the annuity-\fIequivalent\fR amount while staying
invested in equities. It is \fBnot\fR an annuity purchase: there is no mortality
pooling and no income guarantee, and the balance can be depleted by a poor
sequence of early returns.
.IP \(bu 2
The quote site supports ages 40\(en90 only; quote ages above 90 are clamped to
the age-90 payout rate. This is conservative \(em it understates the rising
payout rate at very old ages.
.IP \(bu 2
Annuity payouts are "Average Estimated Quotes" scraped live from
immediateannuities.com, not binding rates from a single insurer. Network access
is required.
.IP \(bu 2
A single invocation is one random path. Run with a fixed
.B --seed
for reproducibility; use the Monte Carlo driver for confidence intervals.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
A reproducible single-life projection:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL --seed 1
.fi
.RE
.PP
A joint-life projection using the lognormal model:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL \\
    --joint-age 63 --joint-gender F --model lognormal
.fi
.RE
.PP
A block bootstrap with 10-year blocks to emphasize inflation persistence:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 70 F CA --model block --block-length 10
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.B withdrawal_projection.py
This program. Exposes \fBbuild_rate_cache()\fR and \fBsimulate_path()\fR for reuse
by a Monte Carlo (many-paths) driver.
.TP
.B annuity_quote.py
Fetches and parses the monthly life-annuity payout.
.TP
.B equity_model.py
The joint equity-return / inflation models.
.TP
.B market_data.py
Embedded historical S&P 500 returns and CPI inflation, 1928\(en2025.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Run with the project virtualenv, which provides NumPy:
.B ~/finance/planning/.venv/bin/python.
Network access to immediateannuities.com is required.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR annuity_quote (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Generated for the personal finance planning workspace.
